---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
---

<Layout title="Beege's Portfolio">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <div class="min-h-[70vh] flex items-center">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="text-primary font-mono mb-4">Hi, I'm</p>
      <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-7xl font-bold mb-4">Beege!</h1>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Or Bryan Berry if you want to be boring and legal</p>
      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-text-muted max-w-2xl mb-8">
        Engineering leader, builder, and community organizer based in Seoul.
      </p>
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <a href="#contact" class="bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors">
          Get in touch
        </a>
        <a href="#personal-projects" class="border border-white/20 hover:border-white/40 px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors">
          See my work
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- About -->
  <Section id="about" title="About">
    <div class="text-text-muted text-lg leading-relaxed max-w-3xl space-y-4">
      <p>
        I'm a software engineer and engineering leader who's spent the last 15 years building things, 9 of which in Seoul. I've worked across gaming, insurance, AI, and medical tech — from Riot Games to PUBG to Lunit, where I led teams building annotation and data management tools for cancer detection AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        I like building things that matter, leading teams that ship, and teaching people who want to learn. I founded CodeSeoul to give developers in Seoul a place to grow, and I'm currently building a startup while exploring medical AI.
      </p>
      <p>
        Georgia Tech grad (Computational Media). American expat. Fluent in English, working on Korean.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <!-- Professional Projects -->
  <Section id="professional-projects" title="Professional Projects">
    <div class="space-y-16">

      <!-- Data Management System -->
      <div class="bg-surface-light rounded-xl p-8 border border-white/10">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-4">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Data Management System</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Company: Lunit
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Roles: Product Manager, Project Manager
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
          Organized and stored extracted DICOM tags, DICOM file references, and clinical study data for use in annotation and ML training. 
          The system was based on an internally defined, standardized field set and format to be used for each image modality. Fields were
          selected and scrubbed in order to maintain privacy for regulatory compliance. Data was organized
          into acquisition projects by vendor, indicating a batch of data that was received. This was critical, as data acquisition projects represented
          clinical significance beyond what could be found in the DICOM tags and clinical study data. Data stewards could specify aliases for manufacturers and devices
          in order to handle ambiguity between different DICOM information (e.g. Fujifilm vs Fujifilm Inc). ML researchers could define splits within the tool,
          specifying which images were used for which purpose (e.g. training, tuning, validation). Splits were versioned, and data in splits was preserved despite 
          future clean-up, in order to ensure reproducibility for EU AI Act compliance. Clocked 300 transactions per second after we set up monitoring for the first time.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">PostgreSQL</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Python</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">DICOM</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Github Actions</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Google Cloud Platform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Hashicorp Terraform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Kubernetes</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Scrum</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Agile Development</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Data Pipeline Platform -->
      <div class="bg-surface-light rounded-xl p-8 border border-white/10">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-4">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Data Pipeline Platform</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Company: Lunit
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Roles: Project Manager
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
          Massively concurrent data processing pipeline for external data ingestion, annotation data preparation, training data preparation, and
          bulk inference on images using in-house AI models.
          Radiology data engineers used the tool to extract pixel data and tag data from DICOM files. Oncology data engineers used the tool to
          generate thumbnails from whole slide images (WSIs) for display in web views. Data engineers would ingest the extracted data into the
          Data Management System, which would then allow the data to be used for annotation and training. The system would routinely process
          hundreds of terabytes of data, scaling accordingly. The system used spot instances and fine-tuned autoscaling behaviors to minimize cost.
          Reduced example inference task from 2 months to less than 24 hours.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">PostgreSQL</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Python</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Prefect</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">DICOM</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Github Actions</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Google Cloud Platform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Hashicorp Terraform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Kubernetes</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Scrum</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Agile Development</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Oncology Annotation Tool -->
      <div class="bg-surface-light rounded-xl p-8 border border-white/10">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-4">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Oncology Annotation Tool</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Company: Lunit
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Roles: Product Manager, Project Manager, DevOps Engineer, Engineering Manager
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
          An internal tool for oncologists to label cells in pathology slides. Oncologists could specify an area of the whole slide image (WSI) for annotation.
          These annotation areas would then be assigned a label set for future labeling, then entered into a queue. Oncologists would then annotate WSI areas in their queue
          by either painting tissue areas, designating points, or drawing contours around cells. Oncologists could zoom in and out deeply on huge WSI images, either to 
          get the context of the broader tissue sample or to see minute details. Nearly every function provided a keyboard shortcut, as annotation speed was critical for cost management.
          The tool supported external, contracted oncology teams accessing the tool, along with external manager permissions scheme and access. Internal radiologists could review
          and give feedback on annotation work. The tool also provided an API to allow machine learning researchers to pull the data to run their training.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">PostgreSQL</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Python</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Django</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">MessagePack</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">WebGL</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Github Actions</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Google Cloud Platform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Hashicorp Terraform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Kubernetes</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Scrum</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Agile Development</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Radiology Annotation Tool -->
      <div class="bg-surface-light rounded-xl p-8 border border-white/10">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-4">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Radiology Annotation Tool</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Company: Lunit
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Roles: Product Manager, Project Manager, DevOps Engineer, Backend Engineer, Engineering Manager
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
          An internal tool for radiologists to label medical images. Radiologists would be assigned an annotation project, where they could either work through a queue 
          or have a pre-assigned pool of images to annotate. Radiologists could manipulate images by zooming, panning, adjusting brightness, adjusting contrast, inverting
          the light in the image, and flipping the image horizontally. Nearly every function provided a keyboard shortcut, as annotation speed was critical for cost management.
          The tool supported chest X-rays (CXR), mammograms (MMG), and digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) images. Radiologists could annotate with polygons, line contours, or points.
          In the case of MMG and DBT images, radiologists could group annotations across images in order to indicate that they represented the same physical object, enforcing
          consistent labels across the annotations. The tool supported multi-window annotation for handling current-prior comparison annotation - that is, annotating a 
          previous medical study and a current medical study concurrently.
          Annotation project managers could specify reviewers, where reviewers could start threads to discuss annotations and provide feedback.
          The tool provided an API to allow machine learning researchers to pull the data to run their training. Once I became product manager and engineering manager of the tool
          and made some progress, radiologists lauded the improvements, saying "this is the smoothest annotation has ever gone."
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">MongoDB</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Python</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">FastAPI</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">DICOM</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Cornerstone</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Github Actions</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Amazon Web Services</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Google Cloud Platform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Hashicorp Terraform</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Kubernetes</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Scrum</span>
          <span class="text-xs bg-primary/20 text-primary px-2 py-1 rounded">Agile Development</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Command and Control System -->
      <div class="bg-surface-light rounded-xl p-8 border border-white/10">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-4">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Command and Control System</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
            Company: Posicube
          </div>
          <div class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-text-muted">
